I know these are not strictly faithful to any one version of the horns on Hellboy's head, but there are so many variations in the movies and comics, that I am confident that you will allow me my small vanity. I designed these bad boys with Tinkercad - not the ideal tool for modelling organic shapes, but they came out OK, IMHO. However, when sliced (Slic3r 7.2) I got the familiar manifold and intersecting facets errors. There are many unions and differences in these things, and Netfabb failed twice to fix the issues. I noticed some strange bridging and infill behavior in the lower layers, and the concavity on top came out different, but otherwise they printed fine. I have not tried a newer version of Slic3r (not optimistic). I won't be offended if you have the tool to fix the errors in the STL and post the fix. UPDATE - Netfabb fix posted (not tested) Red ABS, 0.40mm nozzle, 0.30 mm layers, 33% infill, 3 perimeters (Crappy) Photo editing with GIMP.

How come most coasters are flat and made of something non-absorbent so they're only useful at times when you don't need a coaster?  Try using one of those when there's some humidity on a summer day and your drink is cold, and you end up with a puddle spilling over the edge and defeating the point of having a coaster.  Even the ones made of absorbent stone don't absorb enough.  Cork ones do all right but tend to get pretty ratty and even smelly, and they're hard to find.  
I saw Stanistani's coaster idea and liked the concept of a coaster that had ridges for the moisture to seep into, but people said in reviews that the little bumps didn't do that good a job holding up the cup.  So I decided to make an approach that would have a bit more rigidity at holding up a cup, but still have room for it to drain condensation.  Plus concentric rings just look cool, stylistically speaking.  
I also made a holder that stores six of the coasters stacked since they don't otherwise have any way of keeping themselves in a tidy pile.

A simple print with a bit of a brim to avoid warping.  
Print six of the coasters plus one holder for each set.  Same color or contrasts?  Good question!  I'm tempted to have a white holder and a red, orange, yellow, green, blue, and purple set, but maybe all one color would be more tasteful.  
I've printed one set in blue at 100% scale which fits most of my glasses and cups, and one set in black at 120% scale which fits the bigger plastic tumbler cups.

title: Diving Board Corner Sphere (protect pool solar cover from snags)

description.text:
The way my pool is situated, the only way to wind up the solar cover is to drag it over the diving board. This usually works well, but after a season or two the cover tends to snag on the diving board corners. This thing solves the problem. It is simply a sphere several inches in diameter with a corner notched out. I put the spheres on the corners of the diving board as shown in the photo, and there is no longer a corner to snag the solar cover. You may of course have to adjust the size of the notched out corner to fit your own diving board. Measure it first and then add a few millimeters slack. My diving board was 31mm thick (about 1.25 inches) so I used 34 mm as the cube height used to cut the notch. If your board happens to be 1.25 inches then you win! Otherwise just adjust it in the openscad and have fun in the sun with no snags! NOTE: if your cover is attached to the reel (mine is not) then make sure you put the corners on before you unreel the cover. The spheres should be snug enough that they won't come off as you deploy the cover, then they'll be in place when it's time to wind the cover back up. Instructions:

  • Measure the thickness of your diving board near the corners. If it happens to be near 1.25 inches (31 or so mm) then you can use the stl. Otherwise, edit the openscad file and adjust the height of the cube used to cut the notch from 34 mm to whatever your board is plus a few mm extra.

  • Print 2 of them. When you need to roll up your cover, put them on the board first. No more snags!

  • If you print these out of PLA you might want to spray them with waterproof sealer so they don't degrade.

  • Remove them before people use the pool for swimming, of course.

description.text: set square for the kids learn how to use it and vocabulary too

Game counters for CCGS, such as Magic: The Gathering or Pokémon.  Each counter is actually three pieces: a face with a negative number, a middle button, and a face with a positive number.  They're built this way so you can print both faces directly on your print bed and get a consistent finish between the faces.  Also, the middle piece allows for a third color in your print.  
Each middle "button" has four holes, and each face has two posts, set at a diagonal.  The negative faces have opposing diagonals to the positive, so when you line them up on a button they'll flip on the vertical axis without having to rotate the counter.
I created these with an OpenSCAD routine that has some customizable parameters.  You can change the orientation of the posts (so you could make these flip on the horizontal axis) and you can choose to have a rounded groove in the face instead of a hole punched all the way through.  Of course, you could also change the counter text.  I've only uploaded the models needed to print plus and minus faces for 1 through 4.  Please message me if you're interested in the OpenSCAD file.

Pretty simple.  Take one face, add a drop of epoxy or glue, line the button up with the posts and holes, stick together.  Then put the opposite face on, rotating its posts into the remaining holes on the button.

I mentioned in the summary that I used OpenSCAD -- the OpenSCAD file helps a lot because you can change the orientation, a bit of the ornamentation, the size of the text and the actual text displayed, etc.  I just uploaded the models needed for -1 through +4 because those are the most common needed for gaming.

comments.text: Is the idea that fingers to the right will vibrate when the sound hits a certain higher frequency, and the fingers to the left will vibrate when the sound hits lower frequencies? I just pictured "listening" to Beethoven's 9th, and how much that would actually be able to convey to someone that couldn't hear.
comments.author: jkeegan

comments.text: That's essentially the idea, except that the intention is to reproduce the neurological signals that the cochlea sends to the brain, so the sound information is decomposed with the wavelet transformation. Wavelets give something a bit different from a frequency band decomposition, which you would get from a Fourier transform. That said, there's no reason you couldn't send the Fourier decomposition... if you did, then you're playing with the interesting notion of giving the brain data in a way that it's never experienced before.

title: Lasercut Settlers of Catan board as DXF

description.text:
This is simply a derivative to be used by laser cutters that require DXF format files. I converted this using the latest version of Inkscape (0.48.4). Also had to move a few of the dots around and converts all the fonts to paths. Cutting took about 40 minutes through 4mm MDF. Update1: catan03-1.dxf do not use this without cutting an extra wheat tile
Now has more coloured paths. Also I removed the dice value from the desert as it won't have one in the game. warning, this has the wrong number of tiles so you'll need an extra wheat tile from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:127087 Purple - Boats, possible raster engraving
Green - Text, possible raster engraving
Black - Outlines, engrave cut
Blue - Circle cuts
Red - Tile cuts Update2: catan04-1.dxf - removed due to issues Update3: catan4-2.dxf & tree04-2-tested.dxf
Fixed a few problems that were showing up in the lasercut software but don't have the materials to do a test cut of the full set of tiles. I've also created a new tested single tree tile as I believe this is the tile causing most of the problems so feel free to try this single tile out and see if it works.

Filament clip for 1.75mm filament for plastic spools.
(EDIT : Added 3mm filament version, with 3.3mm hole. The 1.75mm version has a 2mm hole.) Just bought a whole batch of different coloured ABS and wanted to try out the various colours without using a full spool. Just anticipated that unraveling spools will be a nightmare so came up with this super simple clip to hold onto the filament. Didn't like the idea of tape or 'sliding it under'. The flat side is deliberately on the inside as I've found the spools I have have the inside smooth (makes sense) and the outside rim is thicker than the inside. www.madox.net

1)Print
2)Insert loose filament end into the hole
3)Clip onto the plastic spool
4)Profit from not having to deal with unraveling spools

I noticed my belt was being shaved by my printer bearing blocks and decided to use bearings instead of cutting the blocks which would void my warranty. Using Traxxas standard bearings 5x11x4mm I made the bracket to where it barely pushes the belt out of the way, but does the job. I had seen a x axis chain relief part before an so I thought I add one. NOTE: this limits your printer on the x axis to about 7.4 inches instead of 8 because the bearing will hit the wall and cause the belt to slip. If you aren't printing anything that big then you're fine. video of it :
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vrxriDGNV_8 The holes are for m3 bolts and the spacers included space the x-axis chain carrier away so that the m3 bolts can be installed with nuts to hold the bracket nice and sturdy. Comment if you have any questions or concerns.
